{"title_page": "Erik Altieri", "text_new": "'''Erik Altieri''' is the executive director of the [[National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws]] (NORML).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://herald-review.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/poll-as-chicago-contemplates-pot-legalization-decatur-officials-still-skeptical/article_a2b4b6f6-eb83-56c6-95ad-ad49c5f0d80a.html |website=herald-review.com |publisher=[[Herald & Review]] |title=POLL: As Chicago contemplates pot legalization, Decatur officials still skeptical |access-date=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130092648/http://herald-review.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/poll-as-chicago-contemplates-pot-legalization-decatur-officials-still-skeptical/article_a2b4b6f6-eb83-56c6-95ad-ad49c5f0d80a.html# |archive-date=2018-01-30 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2018/04/11/john-boehner-was-a-longtime-opponent-of-marijuana-reform-heres-what-changed-his-mind/?noredirect=on |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |title=John Boehner was a longtime opponent of marijuana reform. Here\u2019s what changed his mind. }}</ref> He assumed the role in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/legalization-spreads-norml-evolves-new-leadership/ |title=As Legalization Spreads, NORML Evolves Under New Leadership |publisher=Marijuana Moment |date=October 2017 |access-date=2018-10-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930081538/https://www.marijuanamoment.net/legalization-spreads-norml-evolves-new-leadership/# |archive-date=2018-09-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> and is the ninth executive director since NORML's founding in 1970.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.freedomleaf.com/freedomleaf-norml-interview/ |title=NORML's New Executive Director Erik Altieri |publisher=\"Freedom Leaf\" |date=2017-02-21 |access-date=2018-10-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020114741/https://www.freedomleaf.com/freedomleaf-norml-interview/# |archive-date=2018-10-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> Previously, he was the organization's Communications Director, PAC Manager, and Federal Lobbyist. He is the youngest person named executive director in the organization's history, an accomplishment recognized by Forbes Magazine when he was named one of Forbes' 30 Under 30 for Law and Policy in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/5a036c5f4bbe6f37dda202fd/2018-30-under-30-law--pol/ |title=Erik Altieri, Forbes 30 Under 30, Law and Society |publisher=Forbes |access-date=2018-10-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723211739/https://www.forbes.com/pictures/5a036c5f4bbe6f37dda202fd/2018-30-under-30-law--pol/# |archive-date=2018-07-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> Altieri is currently based in Washington, DC at NORML's national headquarters where he oversees the organization's federal efforts and orchestrates the strategy for NORML's 165+ state and local level chapters across the country.\n\n==Biography==\nAltieri was born and raised in Northeast Philadelphia and spent the later part of his childhood residing in South Jersey. He became deeply interested in politics and was drawn into advocacy work by the anti-war activism of the early 2000s over the conflicts in Iraq and Afghanistan.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He attended American University in Washington, DC.\n\nAfter college, Altieri became NORML's Communications Director and ran their federal and state lobbying efforts and legislative out-reach, administered NORML\u2019s social media networks and served as a spokesman to the press from 2007-2015. During this time period he also became the manager of NORML PAC, and worked to elect marijuana reform-friendly candidates at all levels of government. In 2015, he left NORML to explore other political issue activism including campaign finance reform and tax policy. He returned to NORML as executive director in 2016 and presently continues to serve in that role.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== References ==\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.vice.com/en_ca/article/9knqgz/it-looks-like-jeff-sessions-is-kicking-off-his-war-on-legal-weed |website=news.vice.com |publisher=[[Vice News]] |title=It looks like Jeff Sessions is kicking off his war on legal weed |access-date=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002080701/https://news.vice.com/en_ca/article/9knqgz/it-looks-like-jeff-sessions-is-kicking-off-his-war-on-legal-weed# |archive-date=2018-10-02 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.in/Canada-just-became-the-second-country-in-the-world-to-legalize-marijuana/articleshow/64669157.cms |website=businessinsider.in |publisher=[[Business Insider India]] |title=Canada just became the second country in the world to legalize marijuana |access-date=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917063448/https://www.businessinsider.in/canada-just-became-the-second-country-in-the-world-to-legalize-marijuana/articleshow/64669157.cms# |archive-date=2018-09-17 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mynews13.com/fl/orlando/politics/2018/07/27/studying-the-marijuana-effect--new-bill-calls-for-research-where-pot-is-legal |website=mynews13.com |publisher=[[News 13]] |title=Studying the marijuana effect: New bill calls for research where pot is legal |access-date=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107214941/http://www.mynews13.com/fl/orlando/politics/2018/07/27/studying-the-marijuana-effect--new-bill-calls-for-research-where-pot-is-legal# |archive-date=2018-11-07 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/apr/11/john-boehner-joins-cannabis-dispensary-board-repor/ |website=washingtontimes.com |publisher=[[The Washington Times]] |title=John Boehner joins cannabis dispensary board: Report |access-date=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426072448/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/apr/11/john-boehner-joins-cannabis-dispensary-board-repor/# |archive-date=2018-04-26 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Altieri, Erik}}\n[[Category:American cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Erik Altieri''' is the executive director of the [[National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws]] (NORML).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://herald-review.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/poll-as-chicago-contemplates-pot-legalization-decatur-officials-still-skeptical/article_a2b4b6f6-eb83-56c6-95ad-ad49c5f0d80a.html |website=herald-review.com |publisher=[[Herald & Review]] |title=POLL: As Chicago contemplates pot legalization, Decatur officials still skeptical |access-date=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130092648/http://herald-review.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/poll-as-chicago-contemplates-pot-legalization-decatur-officials-still-skeptical/article_a2b4b6f6-eb83-56c6-95ad-ad49c5f0d80a.html# |archive-date=2018-01-30 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2018/04/11/john-boehner-was-a-longtime-opponent-of-marijuana-reform-heres-what-changed-his-mind/?noredirect=on |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |title=John Boehner was a longtime opponent of marijuana reform. Here\u2019s what changed his mind. }}</ref> He assumed the role in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/legalization-spreads-norml-evolves-new-leadership/ |title=As Legalization Spreads, NORML Evolves Under New Leadership |publisher=Marijuana Moment |date=October 2017 |access-date=2018-10-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930081538/https://www.marijuanamoment.net/legalization-spreads-norml-evolves-new-leadership/# |archive-date=2018-09-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> and is the ninth executive director since NORML's founding in 1970.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |